if (e.code === 'Comma') {

<script>
//This script is to address some quirkiness of Safari where commas are interchangeable with decimal points on number fields.
//Normal attempts to restrict the comma such as our own validation or .replace(",", "") results in the value of the field being removed entirely.
//Below the keypress itself is being blocked as a workaround to keep our value.
document.getElementById("field133346953").addEventListener("keydown", function blockComma(e) {
if (e.code === 'Comma') {
e.preventDefault();}})
</script>

<div class="fsSection fs1Col fsHidden" id="fsSection133346915">
<div class="fsSectionHeader">
<h2 class="fsSectionHeading">Food & Drinks</h2>
</div>
<div id="fsRow5031315-330" class="fsRow fsFieldRow fsLastRow">
<div class="fsRowBody fsCell fsFieldCell fsFirst fsLast fsLabelVertical fsSpan100" id="fsCell133346916" lang="en" fs-field-type="richtext" fs-field-validation-name="">
<p><u><strong>Drinks</strong></u></p><p>Coca-Cola is a sponsor of the MJCCA, so only Coca-Cola brands may be provided at MJCCA programs and events (e.g. Coke, Dasani, Powerade, Minute Maid,  SmartWater, VitaminWater, AHA)</p><p>Alcoholic beverages may only be served by a licensed bartender.  If serving alcohol, please contact David Fried or Janice Wolf.</p><p><strong><u>Catering</u></strong></p><p>A Kosher Touch is the MJCCA’s kosher caterer of choice.  If the MJCCA is sponsoring an event, A Kosher Touch should be given the opportunity to provide a quote for food at the event.  Contact Wendy Cohen, wendy@sandrasaddedtouch.com.</p><p><strong><u>Kosher Policy</u></strong></p><p>Unless catered by a Kosher vendor, all food, other than kosher fish, must be non-meat. </p><ul><li>Non-meat refers to products that do not contain flesh foods, as well as byproducts of meat and poultry (such as animal gelatins or rennet – for example Jello, marshmallows, or some cheeses). </li><li>Kosher fish refers to fish that have fins and scales. Examples of kosher fish are tuna, grouper, bass, flounder, salmon, etc. Examples of non-kosher fish are catfish, shellfish, shrimp, lobster, marlin, monk fish, mussels, etc.</li></ul><p>If kosher meat is served, the following guidelines will be strictly followed:</p><ul><li>Approval from JCC rabbi / mashgiach.</li><li>Meat must contain AKC accepted hechsher.</li><li>Equipment (grills, utensils, tools) will be stored and reserved for this purpose only.</li><li>Meat and milk products will not be served together.</li><li>Adequate signage will always be used to designate the kashrut status of served foods.</li><li>For all JCC sponsored events, there will always be an AKC (or similarly accepted supervision) food option.</li></ul><p>Please reach out to Rabbi Glusman before ordering or serving food at MJCCA sponsored events.</p><p><a href="https://www.atlantajcc.org/about/facility-rentals/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Kosher Policy for Rentals</a></p><p>To learn more about Jewish Dietary Laws (known as kashrut in Hebrew), go to <a href="http://www.myjewishlearning.com/article/kashrut-101" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">www.myjewishlearning.com/article/kashrut-101</a>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

options.label: Ad Hoc Request - Event Security Checklist

fields.section_text:
Facility Booking (other use) Only select for rentals, meetings, or other events that are not MJCCA programs.

Ad Hoc Request Only select if nothing about your program has changed since the original program request was submitted (or since the most recent change request).  Otherwise, select the "CHANGE" option, which will also make these request forms available.  This ensures that all necessary individuals/departments are kept informed about changes to your program.

Participant responses will be reviewed by the inclusion department.

fields.section_text: Marketing will receive a copy of this request.  Please note that if the deadline has passed, it may be too late to update the Program Guide.

Example Submissions

T-BALL
Boys and Girls, Grades PreK-1
March 3-May 5
PreK (Minors): Sundays, 1:00-2:00 pm
Grades K-1 (Majors): Sundays, 2:00-3:00 pm
T-Ball is an introductory program where your slugger will learn basic baseball skills in a casual and playful environment. During the season, kids will learn skills like fielding and batting. Each meeting will consist of practice and a scrimmage game. In no time, they’ll be ready to step up to the big leagues! Players need to provide their own baseball pants (optional) and bats to play with. Bats should be between the sizes of 27’-29’. Cleats (optional) should not have metal spikes.
Fee: Member $195; Community $275 (8 sessions)


TUMBLING TWOS
Boys & Girls, Ages 1-2
January 7-May 12
Sundays, 9:15-9:45 am
Tumbling Twos teaches basic gymnastics skills and movements. Children will have the opportunity to utilize the preschool gymnastics equipment while learning basic motor and socialization skills. This is a parent-assisted class.
Fee: $225

Players need to provide their own baseball pants (optional) and bats to play with. Bats should be between the sizes of 27’-29’. Cleats (optional) should not have metal spikes.

fields.section_text:
Drinks

Coca-Cola is a sponsor of the MJCCA, so only Coca-Cola brands may be provided at MJCCA programs and events (e.g. Coke, Dasani, Powerade, Minute Maid,  SmartWater, VitaminWater, AHA)

Alcoholic beverages may only be served by a licensed bartender.  If serving alcohol, please contact David Fried or Janice Wolf.

Catering

A Kosher Touch is the MJCCA’s kosher caterer of choice.  If the MJCCA is sponsoring an event, A Kosher Touch should be given the opportunity to provide a quote for food at the event.  Contact Wendy Cohen, wendy@sandrasaddedtouch.com.

Kosher Policy

Unless catered by a Kosher vendor, all food, other than kosher fish, must be non-meat. 

  • Non-meat refers to products that do not contain flesh foods, as well as byproducts of meat and poultry (such as animal gelatins or rennet – for example Jello, marshmallows, or some cheeses). 
  • Kosher fish refers to fish that have fins and scales. Examples of kosher fish are tuna, grouper, bass, flounder, salmon, etc. Examples of non-kosher fish are catfish, shellfish, shrimp, lobster, marlin, monk fish, mussels, etc.

If kosher meat is served, the following guidelines will be strictly followed:

  • Approval from JCC rabbi / mashgiach.
  • Meat must contain AKC accepted hechsher.
  • Equipment (grills, utensils, tools) will be stored and reserved for this purpose only.
  • Meat and milk products will not be served together.
  • Adequate signage will always be used to designate the kashrut status of served foods.
  • For all JCC sponsored events, there will always be an AKC (or similarly accepted supervision) food option.

Please reach out to Rabbi Glusman before ordering or serving food at MJCCA sponsored events.

Kosher Policy for Rentals

To learn more about Jewish Dietary Laws (known as kashrut in Hebrew), go to www.myjewishlearning.com/article/kashrut-101.
